  "texts": [
    "To our knowledge, the earliest use of a continuum model for TBG is in Lopes dos Santos et al. [111].",
    "However, although that work indeed predicted the suppression of the Fermi velocity, Bistritzer and MacDonald [112] were the first to show that the bands became flat across the moiré BZ, and clearly identify the \"magic angle\" property (although this is implicit in the Fermi velocity formula of Ref.",
    "Since the continuum model we write down is precisely that of Bistritzer and MacDonald, we will use this henceforth, in common with the prevailing convention of the field.is measured with respect to the monolayer Γ-pointfoot_1, l = 1, 2 denotes the layer, and σ = A, B indicates the microscopic sublattice, the BM Hamiltonian is5 ⟨p, 1| H BM |p ′, 1⟩ = ℏv F σ * θ/2 • (p -K 1) δ p,p ′ (1) ⟨p, 2| H BM |p ′, 2⟩ = ℏv F σ * -θ/2 • (p -K 2) δ p,p ′ (2) ⟨p, 1| H BM |p ′, 2⟩ = T 1 δ p-p ′,0 + T 2 δ p-p ′,b1+b2 + T 3 δ p-p ′,b2(3)σ * θ/2 = e -(iθ/4)σz (σ x, σ * y)e (iθ/4)σz (4)T 1 = w AA w AB w AB w AA, T 2 = w AA w AB e iϕ w AB e -iϕ w AA, T 3 = w AA w AB e -iϕ w AB e iϕ w AA,(5)where ϕ = 2π 3, v F is the monolayer Dirac velocityfoot_3, and K l is the rotated Dirac wavevector of valley K in layer l. The sublattice degree of freedom has been absorbed into the 2 × 2 matrix structure.",
    "Due to the layer rotation, the intralayer kinetic terms pick up a 'Pauli twist', which represents a small correction in the small-angle limit.",
    "If neglected, this results in a particle-hole symmetry P (PHS)."
